# Global Audit Memory

## Scope Touched
- Queue and signature-queue stack stayed central: `queues/DepositQueue.sol`, `RedeemQueue.sol`, `SignatureQueue.sol`, `SignatureDepositQueue.sol`, `SignatureRedeemQueue.sol` (fee-path divergence, nonce/intent semantics, pause/cancel/settle/checkpoint and claim accounting/liveness).
- Share/claim surface remains high-signal: `managers/ShareManager.sol`, `modules/ShareModule.sol`, `queues/DepositQueue.sol` (authorization and lockup-timing side effects, including third-party claim timing influence).
- Verifier/permission path deepened: `permissions/Verifier.sol` (+ broader `permissions/*`) with attention on custom verifier payload format/decoding mismatch risk.
- Vault/subvault transfer-accounting path gained stronger evidence: `modules/VaultModule.sol`, `modules/SubvaultModule.sol`, `libraries/TransferLibrary.sol` (requested-vs-received amount drift under non-standard ERC20s).
- Fee/accounting manager path still repeatedly revisited: `managers/FeeManager.sol` and queue fee hooks (ordering/consistency across flow variants).
- Broader but lighter scans continued across `oracles/Oracle.sol`, `managers/RiskManager.sol`, `managers/TokenizedShareManager.sol`, `modules/ACLModule.sol`, `modules/CallModule.sol`, factory/config/hook surfaces.

## Issue Directions Seen
- Standard vs signature queue economic-path inconsistency (especially fee hook application) is now a retained direction.
- Verifier intent/encoding mismatches (documented format vs runtime decoding) remain a recurring and high-value direction.
- Transfer/accounting fragility with fee-on-transfer/deflationary/non-standard ERC20 behavior remains active and now better evidenced.
- Payable entrypoint ETH-handling edge cases (unused ETH acceptance/stuck funds) are confirmed as a practical direction.
- Prior recurring directions still relevant: claim-triggered lockup timing manipulation; signature executor/recipient authorization mismatches; oracle lifecycle changes impacting `convertToShares`-dependent queue/risk liveness; queue state integrity across emergency transitions.

## Useful Context
- Cross-agent convergence is strongest on queue + share + verifier + fee/accounting interactions; multi-contract exploitability is most evidenced there.
- Round 5 added retained signals on: signature fee-path bypass, custom verifier decode/docs mismatch, vault/subvault amount-delta drift, and payable-ERC20 ETH trapping.
- `TokenizedShareManager._update` transfer-triggered claim/gas behavior remains a reviewed hotspot but was not retained; treat as unresolved context, not cleared.
- Governance/config and auxiliary modules continue to be touched with comparatively lower evidentiary depth than core queue/share/oracle-verifier paths.
